(9, 'TOUR007', 'Hanoi in my eyes (Shared, Day trip)', 'halong-cruise-tour', 25, 1, '81', '/cat-cat.jpg', '<p style="margin: 0in 0in 7.5pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 15pt; vertical-align: baseline; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="line-height: 20px;">Please kindly read these Terms and Conditions carefully. On booking online or signing our booking form by email, you are deemed to have read and accepted our Terms and Conditions, and are accepting the terms of these conditions on behalf of all persons in the party.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0in 0in 7.5pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 15pt; vertical-align: baseline; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="line-height: 20px;">Trekking In Sappa offers private tours and group tours for free individuals travelers travel to Sapa and surroundings places managed by Vietnam Package Travel. By entering the site you accept our terms and conditions. The policies are subject to change at any time, and it is your responsibility to check them regularly in case there is any change.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0in 0in 7.5pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 15pt; vertical-align: baseline; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="line-height: 20px;">Continuing to use the site after a change has been made is your acceptance of those changes.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0in 0in 7.5pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 15pt; vertical-align: baseline; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><strong><span style="line-height: 20px;">1. Rate quoted in the programs:</span></strong></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0in 0in 7.5pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 15pt; vertical-align: baseline; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="line-height: 20px;">The tour prices on website are valid as stated in the price section in each tour and are net prices and quoted in American dollar per person, inclusive of 5% service charge and exclusive of 10% VAT tax. The promotion price (if any) is applied at the period indicated in the price list.</span></p>\r\n<p style="margin: 0in 0in 7.5pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 15pt; vertical-align: baseline; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><strong><span style="line-height: 20px;">2. Included in quoted programs:</span></strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">All kind of transport as mentioned in the “inclusion” of each tour</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">All accommodations as noted in the itinerary.</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">Homestay in local house</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">Hotel accommodation based on twin/double sharing</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">Meals as specified in the itinerary (B: Breakfast, L: Lunch, D: Dinner);</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">Entrance fees;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">English speaking guide;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">Activities as stated in the itinerary;</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin: 0in 0in 7.5pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 15pt; vertical-align: baseline; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><strong><span style="line-height: 20px;">3. Not included in quoted program prices:</span></strong></p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">Early and/or late check in at hotels unless otherwise stated;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">International airfares unless otherwise stated;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">Visa fee and visa arrangement fee;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">Meals other than specified in the itinerary;</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">Drinks &amp; personal expenses</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">Gratuities and tips</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 20px;">VAT tax</span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p style="margin: 0in 0in 7.5pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 15pt; vertical-align: baseline; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><strong><span style="line-height: 20px;"> </span></strong></p>', '/cat-cat.jpg;/coc-ly-market.jpg;/cross-suspending-bridge.jpg', '2011-06-23,2011-07-23,2011-08-23,2013-10-15,2013-10-22,2013-10-29,2013-11-04,2013-11-11,2013-11-18,2013-11-25,2013-11-06,2013-11-13,2013-11-20,2013-11-27,2013-11-08,2013-11-22,2013-11-29,2013-10-17,20', '2011-09-30', '<p>Hanoi – the capital of Vietnam, the center for economy, politics and Vietnamese culture. It is the second largest city in Vietnam and a must see for tourists.</p>\r\n<p>The oldest and one of the most attractive capital cities in Southeast Asia, Hanoi exudes a rare sense of gracious charm and timelessness. At its core exists a 600-year-old ancient quarter, augmented by a century-old colonial city. Today, the rich cultural heritage of both blends in perfect harmony with growing modernization, as Hanoi claims its position as the heart of Vietnam.</p>\r\n<p>Hanoi is a fascinating blend of East and West, with Chinese influence from centuries of dominance and French design from its colonial past. It is largely unspoiled by modern architecture of the 1970s and 80s and is now going through a modernization that is making it a rising star in Southeast Asia.</p>\r\n<p>Anyone who has ever visited Hanoi will probably tell you that it may be the most beautiful city in all of Asia. People have settled here along the Red River for a thousand years. Nestled along wooded boulevards among the city’s two dozen lakes you will find architectural souvenirs left by all who conquered this great valley, from the Chinese who first came in the last millennium to the French, booted out in our own century.</p>', 1, 1, 0, '2013-11-12 20:01:49', '																																																																																																																																																																																													tour halong																																																																																																																																																																		', '																																																																																																																																																																																													tour halong																																																							', 379, '<ul>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Travel insurance</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Extra food and beverages</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Phone and laundry</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Tips and personal expenses</span></li>\r\n</ul>', '<ul>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Transfer from the hotel to Hanoi Railway station</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Roundtrip transfer in Sapa</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Return train tickets Hanoi â€“ Lao Cai â€“ Hanoi (Soft sleeper with A/C â€“ 4 persons in one cabin)</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">3 nights home-tay in the villages</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">1 night at hotel in Sapa</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Full board meals</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">English speaking guide</span></li>\r\n<li><span style="line-height: 1.3em;">Entrance fees</span></li>\r\n</ul>', '2013-07-18', '2013-12-31', '', '', '', '7:00', 0, '1-3;4-6', 'shared', 20, 1),
(10, 'TOUR002', 'Amazing Vietnam Tour (Shared)', 'amazing-vietnam-tour', 26, 1, '51', '/timthumb-1.jpg', '<h2 style="margin: 10px 0px 15px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-bottom-style: dashed; border-bottom-color: #aeaeae; font-size: 1.4em; font-family: georgia, ''palatino linotype'', palatino, ''times new roman'', times, serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #015fb0; line-height: 1.5em;">Confirmation</h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px 0px 20px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; font-size: 14px; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #444444; line-height: 21px;">Upon receipt of your request, we will check and inform you about availability. Your booking is considered confirmed when we receive your acknowledgement.</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 10px 0px 15px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-bottom-style: dashed; border-bottom-color: #aeaeae; font-size: 1.4em; font-family: georgia, ''palatino linotype'', palatino, ''times new roman'', times, serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #015fb0; line-height: 1.5em;">Cancellations</h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px 0px 20px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; font-size: 14px; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #444444; line-height: 21px;">In the event of cancellation, we will not impose any charges, as we strive to provide the best service and experience to our customers. However, if hotels or transportation contractors apply charges for cancellation, you will have to pay those charges that apply. Cancellation policies vary, depending upon the type of service, the time of year, and the reason for cancellation. We will pass on to you all details of any cancellation policy with our reply upon demand.<br />All cancellation must be informed in writing either by email or fax.</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 10px 0px 15px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-bottom-style: dashed; border-bottom-color: #aeaeae; font-size: 1.4em; font-family: georgia, ''palatino linotype'', palatino, ''times new roman'', times, serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #015fb0; line-height: 1.5em;">Refund</h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px 0px 20px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; font-size: 14px; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #444444; line-height: 21px;">Refunds, and their method will be effected as agreed between you and Amazing Travel Vietnam for unused services, and timely cancellations. Again, we will not charge you any amount for our work. However bank fees, if applicable, will be for your account.</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 10px 0px 15px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-bottom-style: dashed; border-bottom-color: #aeaeae; font-size: 1.4em; font-family: georgia, ''palatino linotype'', palatino, ''times new roman'', times, serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #015fb0; line-height: 1.5em;">Travel Insurance</h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px 0px 20px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; font-size: 14px; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #444444; line-height: 21px;">We highly recommend travelers purchase an personal travel insurance which includes trip cancellation, medical, and other coverage.</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 10px 0px 15px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-bottom-style: dashed; border-bottom-color: #aeaeae; font-size: 1.4em; font-family: georgia, ''palatino linotype'', palatino, ''times new roman'', times, serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #015fb0; line-height: 1.5em;">Tour cost</h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px 0px 20px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; font-size: 14px; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #444444; line-height: 21px;">Tour costs and what inclusion/exclusion are listed on the itinerary for each tour. Unless indicated otherwise on the tour itinerary, the tour fee includes: accommodations in double/twin occupancy, meals, all transportation during the tour, entrance fees , and services of a local tour guide. Tour costs are based in USD and per person.</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 10px 0px 15px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-bottom-style: dashed; border-bottom-color: #aeaeae; font-size: 1.4em; font-family: georgia, ''palatino linotype'', palatino, ''times new roman'', times, serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #015fb0; line-height: 1.5em;">Voucher</h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px 0px 20px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; font-size: 14px; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #444444; line-height: 21px;">Voucher will be issued by Amazing Travel Vietnam after the booked trip is confirmed and payment is completed. A service voucher will be sent by email/fax or snail mail to passenger.</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 10px 0px 15px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-bottom-style: dashed; border-bottom-color: #aeaeae; font-size: 1.4em; font-family: georgia, ''palatino linotype'', palatino, ''times new roman'', times, serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #015fb0; line-height: 1.5em;">Liability</h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px 0px 20px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; font-size: 14px; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #444444; line-height: 21px;">No refunds nor exchanges can be made in respect of accommodation, meals, sightseeing tours, transport or any other services which are included in the tour prices but not utilized by the tour member. Amazing Travel Vietnam is not responsible for any loss, injury or damage sustained by passengers. Additional expenses incurred due to delays or postponement, accidents, inclement weather, political restrictions or any other causes must be covered by the passengers. Passengers are required to have full travel insurance covered. This include trip cancellation, medical emergency evacuation, and other coverage. Airline schedule, train timetable and local conditions may affect accommodation and itineraries. Should this occur, Amazing Travel Vietnam will endeavor to substitute a suitable arrangement of similar value.</p>\r\n<h2 style="margin: 10px 0px 15px; padding: 0px; border-width: 0px 0px 1px; border-bottom-style: dashed; border-bottom-color: #aeaeae; font-size: 1.4em; font-family: georgia, ''palatino linotype'', palatino, ''times new roman'', times, serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #015fb0; line-height: 1.5em;">Complaints/Refunds</h2>\r\n<p style="margin: 0px 0px 20px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; font-size: 14px; font-family: arial, helvetica, sans-serif; vertical-align: baseline; color: #444444; line-height: 21px;">Amazing Travel Vietnam will act as an intermediary between the clients and other services suppliers such as air, train, boat hotels in the event of any complaint.</p>', '\\300x200octaviacombi21367.jpg', '2013-11-14,2013-11-28,2013-12-11,2013-12-25,2014-01-08,2014-01-22,2014-01-31', '2012-05-04', '<div class="div_space" style="padding-bottom: 5px; color: #6b614e; font-family: Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; line-height: 18px;">\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">This is the archetypal Vietnam Tour. The perfect overview of the country from Hanoi to Saigon and beyond. This tour offers a comprehensive insight into the history, people, cultures and environments that make Vietnam such an incredible country to visit.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 15.0pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #763c52; text-transform: uppercase;">TOUR HIGHLIGHTS</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 1 - Arrive in Hanoi</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">With its ochre-colored colonial buildings, tree-lined boulevards and scenic lakes, Hanoi has often been referred to as the Paris of the East. It is a beautiful and bustling city full of character and charm. This afternoon we invite you to join us on a cyclo tour of the Old Quarter. The Old Quarter is a labyrinth of roads, alleyways, and market places and is buzzing with local activity. The cyclo is the perfect way to sit back and soak up the dynamism of the place. We Finish at Hoan Kiem Lake (Lake of the Restored Sword). This evening we enjoy a traditional water-puppet performance – a uniquely northern Vietnamese art form depicting scenes of rural life and episodes of national history. This art is over a thousand years old and the performance is accompanied by live music. The skill of the puppeteers is legendary and you cannot help but be captivated by their performance.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 2 - Exploring Hanoi</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">This morning we take a tour of the city. We begin at the historic Ho Chi Minh Mausoleum, an imposing monument lavishly built using marble and granite, and where the preserved body of “Uncle Ho” resides. Visitors are permitted pay their respects to this revered man himself. A short walk from the mausoleum is the lotus shaped, One Pillar Pagoda – resting on a single stone pillar emerging from the water. We then wind our way to the Temple of Literature, the first University in Vietnam. Created for the sons of mandarins, it is the ideal; place for an overview of Hanoi history and culture. In the afternoon, we visit the excellent Museum of Ethnology; this well designed museum offers a fascinating insight into Vietnam’s natural and cultural history, as well as its 54 ethnic minority groups. The evening is left free you to enjoy some of Hanoi’s wonderful nightspots.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 3 - Drive Hanoi to Halong Bay. Embark on Halong Bay Cruise</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">Today we leave the frenetic city of Hanoi behind and head east to UNESCO listed Halong Bay. Upon arrival we are met by our crew and board the traditional style junk that will be home for the next 2 nights. Aboard this luxury boat we will be well looked after, our cozy cabins are en suite, sumptuous fresh seafood meals will be prepared and there is a well stocked bar.  We set out into the emerald waters of the Gulf of Tonkin to explore the hundreds of limestone islands and islets. The islands are peppered with caves and grottoes and we’ll have the opportunity to explore some of these. We’ll also stop to visit some of the floating communities in the bay; we can take a short tour while our crew picks up some fresh fish for tonight’s dinner. As the day draws to an end a sundowner on the top deck is the perfect way to watch the sunset fade into a night under the stars.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 4 - Exploring Halong Bay</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span class="tbold" style="font-weight: bold;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;"><img src="images/timthumb 1.jpg" alt="" /></span></span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">Rise early to catch a stunning sunrise among the limestone islands, which rise from the waves like dragons’ teeth. Then our cruise continues. Staying 2 nights in the Bay allows us to explore deeper into the bay, escaping the majority of the tourists and allowing us to enjoy a more unique cruise experience. You may like to take the option for some sea kayaking and/or swimming from the beach on one of the islands. A last night dinner is served and then there is time for a last night drink under the stars.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 5 - Finish Cruise and return to Hanoi</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">After breakfast, there is a last opportunity for a swim or simply relax on deck and soak up the final views of this magical bay. Upon our return to the port we say our farewells to our crew. Our next short journey takes us to the charming and village of Yen Duc.  Limestone mountains, palm tree, rice fields and the Kinh Thay River form the backdrop for Yen Duc village. Here it really is as though life has stood still for locals who follow and agricultural way of life little changed since the time of their ancestors. We’ll have some time to get to know our hosts, share some tea, or, you may like to try your hand at fishing or help with the gardening. Your coming to this village helps to promote and preserve local tradition and culture in Yen Duc Village, an ideal model for a community based project. When our time here is finished we make our way back to Hanoi.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 6 - Fly to Hue</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">After breakfast we make the short flight to Hue. Hue was the capital of a unified Vietnam during the Nguyen Dynasty (1802-1945) and is now a UNESCO listed site. It’s a wonderful city! The pace of life is decidedly slower than most other Vietnamese cities, the people are laid back, the architecture is atmospheric and the historical monuments are abundant! Hue also has its own Royal cuisine, which is popular all over Vietnam. This afternoon we take a Dragon Boat trip on the Perfume River to visit the iconic Thien Mu Pagoda. We then visit the majestic Tomb of Emperor Ming Mang. This is a truly tranquil place, the manicured gardens are dotted with water features, the tomb is protected by a number of stone guardians, however, no one knows the true location of the real emperors tomb!</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 7 - In Hue</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span class="tbold" style="font-weight: bold;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;"><img src="images/timthumb 2.jpg" alt="" /></span></span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">Our explorations of Hue continue today with a visit to the Forbidden Purple City. This place was reserved solely for the Emperors. The entire area was almost completely destroyed during the Tet offensive in 1969. Both sides lost all measure of restraint as almost the entire city was destroyed. Much of it has now been restored and it is a fascinating place to visit. We’ll also take some time to look around the Citadel, a wonderful residential area of dilapidated homes, historical building, gardens and rice fields. The people are very friendly and the area receives surprisingly few tourists. On the way back we’ll make a stop at Dong Ba market. This is a great example of a local Vietnamese market, Hue conical hats are said to be the best in all of Vietnam! In the evening we visit a private home in the citadel, where we sample some of the dishes from the Emperors Court whilst listening to musicians playing music from the era.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 8 - Drive to Hoi An Via the Hai Van Pass, Cham Museum and Marble Mountain</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">This morning we make an early start and drive on the most scenic stretch of Highway 1. We climb up to the Hai Van Pass (“Pass of the Ocean Clouds”). The scenery on the way up is stunning as are the views from the top. We continue on our way to Danang and stop at the Cham Museum. Housed in a beautiful colonial villa this is the best collection of sculpture from the Cham Empire anywhere in the world. Later we stop just outside of Danang at Marble Mountain. A very auspicious place for the Vietnamese. The 5 limestone peaks are said to represent the 5 elements. There are many caves with to explore, a pagoda and numerous Buddha statues and carvings. We the continue to Hoi An and arrive in the late afternoon.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 9 - In Hoi An</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">Between the 17th and 19th centuries, Hoi An was a prosperous trading port. Today, this World Heritage-listed ancient town boasts well-preserved buildings, pedestrianized streets and unique cuisine, allowing visitors a glimpse of its illustrious past. The narrow lanes are lined with the historical building, pagodas, and merchant’s houses and are ideal for personal exploration. This morning we take you on a walking tour of the Old Quarter taking in all the highlights and character of this bustling little town. We leave the afternoon free for relaxation or shopping – Hoi An is a shoppers paradise with all kinds of wonderful items on offer. It is also famous for its clothes tailors. There is also Cua Dai Beach 5kms away, this makes a pleasant cycle or we can assist in other travel arrangements.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 10 - In and around Hoi An</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 0.0001pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">Today there are a number of options; it is possible to visit the ruins of My Son the ancient Cham Kingdom. These brick built temples were built between the 4<sup><span style="border: none windowtext 1.0pt; mso-border-alt: none windowtext 0in; padding: 0in;">th</span></sup></span><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;"> </span><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">and 13<sup><span style="border: none windowtext 1.0pt; mso-border-alt: none windowtext 0in; padding: 0in;">th</span></sup></span><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; mso-bidi-font-size: 11.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;"> </span><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">centuries during the time that the Champa Empire ruled all of Southern and Central Vietnam. Or you may like to try your hand at Vietnamese cooking. This world famous cuisine is surprisingly simple to re-create. Your teacher will take you to the market where various ingredients and produce are explained and purchased for the lesson itself. Expert tuition is offered and you get to test the fruits of your labor for lunch or dinner! Alternatively, you may like to take a lifestyle tour around the surrounds of Hoi An, visiting the fish market early on and then investigating some of the many cottage industries in the area. A fascinating insight into daily life in the countryside!</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 11 - Drive to Danang, Fly to Saigon</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">After breakfast we leave delightful Hoi An behind and fly to the bustling metropolis that is Saigon. Now officially named Ho Chi Minh City, it has a very different feel to its Northern counterpart. Although still obviously Vietnamese the atmosphere is entirely different. It’s a city of contrasts, skyscrapers sore into the clouds dwarfing the colonial buildings on the ground. Old ladies chew beetle nut and sell coconut juice to sophisticated young couples riding on modern Japanese motorbikes. This afternoon we take a walking tour of the cities major sites, including the sobering War Remnants Museum, the Presidential Palace (The World’s media broadcasted images of North Vietnamese tanks crashing through its gates), and some of the colonial-era landmarks such as Notre Dam Cathedral, the Post Office and the Continental Hotel.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 12 - The Cao Dai Temple at Tay Ninh and the Cu Chi Tunnels</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">This morning we leave the bustling streets of the city behind and make our way to Tay Ninh, the Headquarters for the Cao Dai religion – a unique religion, attempting to end the conflicts caused by different religions by representing aspects of many religions under the banner of one. We visit the main Cathedral (which looks like something out of a fantasy film) in time for the 12 o’clock service. It’s an enchanting experience!</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">After a local lunch, we continue to the Cu Chi Tunnels, an extraordinary network of tunnels used by the Vietnamese Communists to escape American bombing. Entire villages were forced underground for their very survival. There were around 250km of tunnels home to up to 16000 people at any one time.  The tunnels were also used for strategic military purposes, the Viet Cong were able to launch attacks on American bases overhead and then disappear into their warren of tunnels. It’s a fascinating insight into the industrious and tenacious war effort of the Vietnamese. It is possible for the daring to get down and dirty and experience the tunnels for yourselves.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 13 - Journey to the Mekong Delta</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">We make an early start and head south to the Mekong Delta. This is a incredible part of the country, so different to anywhere else visited on this tour. Lusciously green and fertile this is the “Land of the Nine Dragons”, a name that refers to the 9 rivers that form the delta. It’s the rice bowl of the country and produces enough rice annually to feed the entire nation. Fruits, vegetable and fish are all major produce here as well.  On our way to Cantho, the economic capital of the Delta, we’ll stop at vibrant floating markets, visit the local cottage industries and take a trip on a local sampan through some of the narrower canals, stopping for a local speciality lunch of Elephant Ear fish, springs rolls and fresh fruits. We arrive in Cantho in the late afternoon in time to enjoy a lovely walk on the colourful and busy riverside where families bring their children and young couples enjoy the romantic ambience.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin-bottom: 0.0001pt; text-align: justify; line-height: normal; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 13.5pt; font-family: ''Times New Roman'',''serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: red;">Day 14 - Floating Markets of Cai Rang</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="margin: 0in 7.5pt 7.5pt 11.25pt; text-align: justify; line-height: 13.5pt; background-position: initial initial; background-repeat: initial initial;"><span style="font-size: 9.0pt; font-family: ''Arial'',''sans-serif''; mso-fareast-font-family: ''Times New Roman''; color: #333333;">We rise early this morning and board a boat, which takes us on the river to the regions largest floating market. Hundreds of vessels advertise their wares by attaching them to long poles that everyone can see.  People come here to buy in bulk and we can observe not only the hustle and bustle of typical market barter and exchange but also entire boatloads of fresh produce are transferred from one boat to another. It’s a blur of boats, conical hats and human activity. We then return to Cantho and prepare for our onwards travel arrangements; either to Saigon or on to neighbouring Cambodia.</span></p>\r\n<p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify;"> </p>\r\n</div>', 1, 0, 0, '2013-11-12 08:34:03', '																																																																																																																																																																																																											tour halong																																																																																																																																																																																											', '																																																																																																																																																																																																											tour halong																																									', 379, '<ul style="margin: 0px 0px 10px 30px; padding: 0px; border: 0px; width: 690px; font-family: OpenSansRegular, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif; li